******
[1]
Date: Thu 20 Nov 2008
Source: New Era, Windhoek, Namibia [edited]
<http://www.newera.com.na/article.php?articleid=885>


Omaheke on Foot-and-Mouth Disease Alert
---------------------------------------
The Ministry of Agriculture, Water and Forestry has intensified
efforts to prevent the spread of foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) from
Botswana into the eastern parts of Namibia. Following an outbreak of
the disease at Ghanzi, a town close to the Namibian eastern border,
officials from the ministry in the Omaheke Region have been holding
meetings with farming communities to sensitise them on the dangers of FMD.

The officials last week held a meeting at Otjombinde. Farmers from
the Eiseb Block area also attended the meeting, while a similar
meeting was held this week at Corridor 13 in the Aminuis
constituency. In addition to the meeting, veterinary service
officials assisted by police officials have also been patrolling the
border fence to ensure that animals do not cross the border, as well
as repair parts of the fence that might be damaged.

An official in the Ministry of Agriculture, Water and Forestry at
Gobabis, Engelbertha Sorogwe, informed New Era that border officials
have been taking extra precautions to prevent the disease from
spreading into Namibia. Apart from banning the importation of all
animal products from the Ghanzi area, cars entering Namibia are being
sprayed with a disinfectant.

She noted that one of the common ways that FMD spreads is through the
movement of people. She added that the virus is carried on shoes,
clothes, luggage, bedding, interior and exterior of vehicles and on
tyres and so forth and thus all these items are being sprayed at the border.

Another means of infection is through the movement of infected
livestock such as cattle, goats and sheep.

"The movement of meat, milk, skins and other animal by-products is
also a serious source of infection and thus it has been banned for now."

She added that although FMD is not transmitted through water,
congregation of animals at water points will increase the spread of
the disease.

FMD is a highly infectious disease and has become a serious concern
in the trade of cloven-hoofed animals and their products. Importing
countries will not accept any product that originates from a zone
where the disease is occurring or has occurred in the recent past.

Sorogwe noted that it is important that farming communities work hard
to stop the disease from spreading into the country.

The management and control of FMD is governed by strict regulations
contained in the marketing agreement between Namibia and the European
Union (EU). These regulations are very clear in their description of
the control of FMD and are implemented by the department of
veterinary services.

[Byline: Kuvee Kangueehi]

